snippet.textDisplay:
I have endometriosis as well and I completely understand how sucky it is when you get a flare up. You just want to hide from the world and other people just don't get it. I got a formal warning from my employer for having "too many sick days" of which I had doctor's certificates for each and every one due to my endometriosis and in Australia that is unlawful of them to have done. It adds so much extra stress on an already horrible situation when others feel the need to bring you down for it. Much love xx
edit: I frankly don't see how mentioning fertility is even relevant with all of this, but since it's already been brought up, I have 4 kids and endometriosis. Of course its possible to get pregnant and have it.

snippet.textDisplay:
To all the women out there suffering from endometriosis, I have a story to tell. I'm an MD. During my first year of practice a woman came along with the patient. She had a young girl in her arms and she was caressing her and loving her like she was her most precious. Through small talk I came to know that she had adopted the little girl and had grade IV endo. She had had multiple surgeries and didnt think she'll ever conceive. I offered the comfort that I could but like all the doctors she'd been to, I too, told her that it's almost impossible for her to naturally conceive.

The next time she came to visit me, she had another baby in her arms. Her little girl was happily jumping around and she was loving her the same but this new baby had my attention. She told me it was her baby. Her own baby ! Naturally conceived! She wasn't using any medication and had given up then this miracle happened.

Its been more than 5 years but this is still the most incredibly beautiful thing I've witnessed.
Love and prayers for all 💕💕

snippet.textDisplay:
Everyone: "Why don't you just get a hysterectomy if you're in pain all of the time?"
Me: "Why don't you cut off your balls and penis?" Then we can talk "Why don't you stick a hot torch up your vagina?" Then we can talk.
I would never ever ask someone personal questions about their private parts. So don't ask me about mine. It's pretty simple. I don't understand why this happens to women with endometriosis/PCOS. I would love to sit down with each person and explain that a hysterectomy wouldn't even help. Or that it's my fertility and I'll talk about it if I want to. But I don't have time or emotional energy to do this. I sit at home and cry enough about it. There is no cure. Let's treat it like you would with a "normal" everyday person. If you wouldn't ask them about their private business, literally, then don't ask me. Don't ask Tati.
